Spoiler conjecture ahead,
>their leader was the literal god of death
The stories of characters like Marika's and Ranni's "shadows" is a bit more tragic than that (yep, Blaidd too). The runes that comprise those inscribed upon the Elden Ring govern the laws of reality throughout The Lands Between. Marika cherrypicked death as a reality out of the Golden Order, effectively making all who live under it immortal, even to their horrific detriment; it didn't solve the problems of decay, rot, or just living on as a dried out husk entirely. There's a reason only the Tarnished look like living people.
In any case, Marika entrusted the death rune (which she/Radagon deliberately carved out of the Elden Ring) to Maliketh, who was a very good boy, but ultimately failed—it's why he's insane. It was his only purpose, and no matter how much he tries to fix it, Godwyn's semi-living, eldritch, soulless body is slowly leaking death as a concept into TLB. It's partly why Fia's personal mission is so important: the death rune being broken means that it's uncontrollable, unbound by any law whatsoever; it's also imperfect, resulting in deathless spirits that pepper the land. Neither Miquella nor Fortissax could stop it; the former inscribed a prayer on a sword for that purpose.
Maliketh was supposed to be the only one who could kill a God after he reigned in the Godskin cult, but Ranni completely undid that.
